\par \pard\plain \s1\cf1{\*\hyphen2\hyphlead2\hyphtrail2\hyphmax0}\rtlch\af1\afs24\lang1033\ltrch\dbch\af1\afs24\langfe1033\loch\f1\fs24\lang1033\rtlch\afs20\ltrch\dbch\afs20\loch\fs18 {\ltrch\loch\f1 \tab This is a reproduction of a lead ruler or "plummet marker", as described in "Scribes and Illuminators" (c.f.).  Such tools were used by scribes between the 12th and 14th centuries for making guide lines on manuscripts prior to calligraphing them.}
\par 
\par {\ltrch\loch\f1{\b Method:}}
\par {\ltrch\loch\f1 \tab I carved a two-part mold out of soapstone and cast pewter in it.  I then trimmed and filed the resulting pewter ruler.}
\par 
\par {\ltrch\loch\f1{\b Period Practice:}}
\par \pard\plain \s1\cf1{\*\hyphen2\hyphlead2\hyphtrail2\hyphmax0}\rtlch\af1\afs24\lang1033\ltrch\dbch\af1\afs24\langfe1033\loch\f1\fs24\lang1033\rtlch\afs20\ab\ltrch\dbch\afs20\ab\loch\fs18\b 
\par \pard\plain \s1\cf1{\*\hyphen2\hyphlead2\hyphtrail2\hyphmax0}\rtlch\af1\afs24\lang1033\ltrch\dbch\af1\afs24\langfe1033\loch\f1\fs24\lang1033\ltrch\loch\fs18{\ltrch\loch\f1{{\b0\f1 \tab }{\ul Material}: The article says that the original was made of lead, but doesn't go into its purity (lead was often alloyed with bismuth, which was mistaken for lead in period, as well as with tin and/or antimony).}}
\par \pard\plain \s1\cf1{\*\hyphen2\hyphlead2\hyphtrail2\hyphmax0}\rtlch\af1\afs24\lang1033\ltrch\dbch\af1\afs24\langfe1033\loch\f1\fs24\lang1033\rtlch\afs20\ltrch\dbch\afs20\loch\fs18 
\par \pard\plain \s1\cf1{\*\hyphen2\hyphlead2\hyphtrail2\hyphmax0}\rtlch\af1\afs24\lang1033\ltrch\dbch\af1\afs24\langfe1033\loch\f1\fs24\lang1033\ltrch\loch\fs18{\ltrch\loch\f1{{\b0\ulnone\f1 \tab }{\ul Method}: From looking at the photo of the original, I am convinced it was {\b cast} rather than, say, being hammered or carved, though I may be wrong.  I have no way of knowing for sure what sort of mold the original was cast in -- possibly stone, sand, or one 
of a number of other materials -- but I judged that the straight edge on the ruler would be hard to produce using sand casting (and that therefore neither I nor the original caster in period would want to try), and so I settled on soapstone for my mold. }}
