\par \pard\plain \s1\cf1{\*\hyphen2\hyphlead2\hyphtrail2\hyphmax0}\rtlch\af1\afs24\lang1033\ltrch\dbch\af1\afs24\langfe1033\loch\f1\fs24\lang1033\rtlch\afs20\ab\ltrch\dbch\afs20\ab\loch\fs18\b 
\par \pard\plain \s1\cf1{\*\hyphen2\hyphlead2\hyphtrail2\hyphmax0}\rtlch\af1\afs24\lang1033\ltrch\dbch\af1\afs24\langfe1033\loch\f1\fs24\lang1033\ltrch\loch\fs18{\ltrch\loch\f1{{\b0\ulnone\f1 \tab }{\ul Things done Accurately}:}}
\par \pard\plain \s1\cf1{\*\hyphen2\hyphlead2\hyphtrail2\hyphmax0}\rtlch\af1\afs24\lang1033\ltrch\dbch\af1\afs24\langfe1033\loch\f1\fs24\lang1033\li360\ri0\fi-360\rtlch\afs20\ltrch\dbch\afs20\loch\fs18 {\ltrch\loch\f1 I cut the soapstone slabs with a hand-saw and polished them with hand tools, with sand-paper, and against one another.}
\par {\ltrch\loch\f1 I carved the ruler shape into the mold by hand, as well as the sprue channel.}
\par {\ltrch\loch\f1 I poured the molten pewter by hand, with a small ladle.}
\par {\ltrch\loch\f1 I cut off the sprue and the flashing, and filed the ruler, all with hand tools.}
\par {\ltrch\loch\f1 I believe that the ruler is the correct size.  Its size closely matches the width of the pages in several period English books of hours that I saw once in a museum.}
\par \pard\plain \s1\cf1{\*\hyphen2\hyphlead2\hyphtrail2\hyphmax0}\rtlch\af1\afs24\lang1033\ltrch\dbch\af1\afs24\langfe1033\loch\f1\fs24\lang1033\rtlch\afs20\ltrch\dbch\afs20\loch\fs18 
\par \pard\plain \s1\cf1{\*\hyphen2\hyphlead2\hyphtrail2\hyphmax0}\rtlch\af1\afs24\lang1033\ltrch\dbch\af1\afs24\langfe1033\loch\f1\fs24\lang1033\ltrch\loch\fs18{\ltrch\loch\f1{{\b0\ulnone\f1 \tab }{\ul Places Where I Diverged From Accuraccy}:}}
\par \pard\plain \s1\cf1{\*\hyphen2\hyphlead2\hyphtrail2\hyphmax0}\rtlch\af1\afs24\lang1033\ltrch\dbch\af1\afs24\langfe1033\loch\f1\fs24\lang1033\li360\ri0\fi-360\rtlch\afs20\ltrch\dbch\afs20\loch\fs18 {\ltrch\loch\f1 After carving the ruler shape into the mold by hand, I polished it with a dremel tool.}
\par {\ltrch\loch\f1 I also used a dremel to carve the vine pattern into the mold.}
\par \pard\plain \s1\cf1{\*\hyphen2\hyphlead2\hyphtrail2\hyphmax0}\rtlch\af1\afs24\lang1033\ltrch\dbch\af1\afs24\langfe1033\loch\f1\fs24\lang1033\rtlch\afs20\ltrch\dbch\afs20\loch\fs18 
\par \pard\plain \s1\cf1{\*\hyphen2\hyphlead2\hyphtrail2\hyphmax0}\rtlch\af1\afs24\lang1033\ltrch\dbch\af1\afs24\langfe1033\loch\f1\fs24\lang1033\ltrch\loch\fs18{\ltrch\loch\f1{{\b0\ulnone\f1 \tab }{\ul Changes Made On Purpose}:}}
\par \pard\plain \s1\cf1{\*\hyphen2\hyphlead2\hyphtrail2\hyphmax0}\rtlch\af1\afs24\lang1033\ltrch\dbch\af1\afs24\langfe1033\loch\f1\fs24\lang1033\li360\ri0\fi-360\rtlch\afs20\ltrch\dbch\afs20\loch\fs18 {\ltrch\loch\f1 Rather than using pure lead or period lead pewter, I used modern lead-free pewter, a tin/antimony/copper alloy.  We like our scribes and don't want to give them lead poisoning, accurate or not.}
\par {\ltrch\loch\f1 The design on the face of the artifact is the name "ROGERU" (other excavated pieces not photographed bear other names).  Because I plan to offer these rulers for sale, I opted for a more generic vine pattern, which I feel is true to the spirit of the origi
nal (I personally find it hard to tell the difference from the photograph.  I felt putting the name on my version would be overly specific: how many people named Rogeru do you know who are calligraphers and accuracy enthusiasts?}
\par {\ltrch\loch\f1 The bottom edge of the artifact is clearly curved.  The top edge also appears to have a few slight curves.  How, then, was it to be used as a straightedge, if it doesn't have a straight edge?  My theory is that the top edge was indeed straight when the art
ifact was cast, but that being buried in the ground for five hundred years has not been kind to it, and has changed its shape slightly.  In keeping with this theory, I have given my reproduction as straight an edge as I was capable of.  I'm sure that if I 
buried it until the year 2500 it would look much more like the photograph.}
